talculator
==========

a GTK 3 based scientific calculator

This project is a fork of galculator, supporting tabs for multiple instances.
talculator now uses libqalculate as its computation engine (arbitrary precision)
and is GTK3-only.

For installation information see the INSTALL file.
For a list of shortcuts, see doc/shortcuts
There is a short man page (man talculator)
Information on algebraic expression input can be found below.
For talculator-specific development, documentation, and issue tracking, see
https://github.com/megnu/talculator.
For historical galculator information, see http://galculator.sf.net.

Algebraic Input
===============

talculator accepts typed expressions in Algebraic notation (with RPN available
as the second notation mode). This section gives an overview of supported
expression input and syntax.

Algebraic input accepts decimal numbers as well as hexadecimal, 
binary and octal numbers. The latter three have to be entered with a prefix:

Number base   Prefix(es)   Example
-----------   ---------    -------
decimal       none         -3.1415
hexadecimal   0x or 0h     0xAF
binary        0b           0b1001
octal         0o           0o777

All algebraic operations and functions are supported. The 
following table lists all available operations:

Operation                 identifier
---------                 ----------
+, -, *, /                +, -, *, /
percent (postfix)         %
power x^y                 ^
module (MOD)              mod, MOD
left shift (LSH)          <<
right shift (INV + LSH)   >>
AND                       &, and, AND
OR                        |, or, OR
XOR                       xor, XOR

Let's speak of factorial and complement as functions. Most functions' arguments
has to be enclosed by brackets. Therefore sin 3 is not allowed and has to be 
written as sin(3). User defined functions can be used in algebraic input
without restrictions.

Function                     Function identifier   Example
--------                     -------------------   -------
Trigonometric functions
Sine, Cosine, Tangent        sin, cos, tan         sin(0.5)
their inverse                asin, acos, atan      asin(0.5)
their hyperbolic variants    sinh, cosh, tanh      sinh(0.5)
and the inverse of those     asinh, acosh, atanh   asinh(0.5)
natural logarithm (base e)   ln                    ln(3)
logarithm (base 10)          log                   log(3)
square root                  sqrt                  sqrt(3)
factorial                    !                     (3)!, 3! (brackets optional)
complement                   ~                     ~(3) (brackets mandatory)

If parsing encounters a syntax error, the input text is turned red.

Paper Mode
==========

Since version 1.3.0 talculator features a paper mode, which offers a very 
simple GUI along with the same expression engine. In the entry
field, enter expressions using the same rules as algebraic input.
Hitting return or clicking the button to the right will evaluate the expression 
and add it as well as the result to the list view above. Double click on any 
row of that list view to copy the corresponding expression to the entry field.

User defined functions
======================

Since version 1.2.1 talculator also features user defined functions. They can 
be called with the fun button next to the constant button and work like the 
other function buttons like sin, cos, etc. (except that inverse and hyperbolic 
are not supported). User functions can be defined in the Preferences dialog 
(Functions page). The function name can be any string beginning with a letter. 
So far, only a single variable is allowed. Expression gives the string 
expression of the function with respect to the specified variable:

Function   Name   Variable   Expression
--------   ----   --------   ----------
f(x)=1-x   f      x          1-x

User defined functions can depend on other user functions:

Function             Name   Variable   Expression
--------             ----   --------   ----------
g(x)=1/(1-x)=1/f(x)  g      x          1/f(x)

User functions can also be called from algebraic typed input.

Some random notes
=================

Left shifting is done with the LSH button.
3 << 4 	"shift 3 four times to the left" 	3 LSH 4 =
As a right shift is somehow the inverse of a left shift, right shifting is done 
by first activating INV and than clicking the LSH button:

23 >> 5 	"shift 23 five times to the right" 	23 INV LSH 5

You can change number base, angle base and the notation mode by simply clicking 
on the corresponding module in the display's second line.

Arithmetic evaluation is powered by libqalculate and uses arbitrary precision.
In integer base modes (HEX/OCT/BIN), effective ranges and overflow behavior are
determined by the configured word size and signedness.

If in hexadecimal, octal or binary signed mode, a negative number won't be 
represented with a leading minus but as 2's complement with respect to the 
chosen variable length.

Brackets follow explicit expression semantics:
- ')' is only accepted when there is a matching open bracket.
- Empty braces () are treated as syntax errors.
- '=' with unmatched '(' is a syntax error (no implicit auto-close).
- Implicit multiplication is supported around braces, e.g. 2(3+4) == 2*(3+4),
  and )( is treated as )*(.

Percent follows explicit calculator-style semantics and is distinct from modulo:
- '%' is percent (postfix), and MOD/mod is modulo.
- X*Y% = X*(Y/100)
- X/Y% = X/(Y/100)
- X+Y% = X + X*(Y/100)
- X-Y% = X - X*(Y/100)
- Y% = Y/100

Input parsing is strict calculator-style in all modes (basic/scientific/paper):
- Unknown identifiers/words are rejected.
- User-defined constants and user-defined functions from Preferences are accepted
  in typed expressions by name (functions require parentheses, e.g. f(3)).
- Tab references `Tab1`..`Tab6` (case-insensitive) are accepted in typed input
  and resolve to each tab's current display value; missing tabs resolve to `0`.
- HEX/OCT/BIN base semantics are preserved, including A-F as digits in HEX mode.
- `log(...)` is treated as base-10 logarithm, while `ln(...)` is natural logarithm.
- Word operators follow bitwise calculator semantics (`and`, `or`, `xor`, `not`).

There is a simple plausibility check for the character choosen as thousand's
separator: it must not be a number in the configured number base and for
a decimal number base neither decimal point nor "e" (exponent identifier
string) nor "-" (minus).

